      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before assembly or use.</strong> Failure to follow safety instructions can result in serious injury.
      </div>

      <h3>General Safety Rules</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Keep work area clean and well-lit. Cluttered benches and dark areas invite accidents.</li>
        <li>Do not operate in explosive atmospheres or near flammable liquids, gases, or dust.</li>
        <li>Keep bystanders, children, and visitors away while operating.</li>
        <li>Store idle tools out of reach of children and untrained persons.</li>
        <li>Do not leave tool running unattended; turn power off and wait until the blade stops completely.</li>
        <li>Make the workshop childproof with padlocks, master switches, or by removing starter keys.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Electrical Safety</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Verify outlet voltage is compatible with nameplate (120V, within 10%).</li>
        <li>The tool has a polarized plug (one blade wider than the other). Do not modify the plug.</li>
        <li>Avoid body contact with grounded surfaces (pipes, radiators, ranges, refrigerators).</li>
        <li>Do not expose to rain or wet conditions.</li>
        <li>Replace damaged cords immediately.</li>
        <li>Use outdoor extension cords marked "W-A" or "W" when working outside.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Miter Saw Safety Rules</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use only blades rated 4,800 RPM or greater.</li>
        <li>For bevel or compound cuts, adjust the sliding fence clear of the blade path and guard system.</li>
        <li>Use clamps to support workpieces whenever possible. Keep hands outside the "No Hands" zone.</li>
        <li>Do not reach behind the saw blade or fence to hold or support the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Never cross your hand over the intended line of cutting.</li>
        <li>Always disconnect power before making adjustments or attaching accessories.</li>
        <li>This saw is intended for wood and wood-like products. Do not use abrasive cutoff wheels for ferrous metals.</li>
        <li>Inspect workpieces for nails, warping, or bowing before cutting.</li>
        <li>Let the blade reach full speed before contacting the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Always wait for the blade to stop completely before raising it from the workpiece.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Extension Cord Sizing:</strong> Use a 3-wire cord with adequate gauge for the length. For 10&ndash;12 amp draw: 16 AWG up to 50 ft, 14 AWG up to 100 ft, 12 AWG up to 150 ft.
      </div>

      <h3>Electrical Requirements</h3>
      <p>Connect to a 120V, 15-amp branch circuit with a 15-amp fuse or circuit breaker. Using the wrong size fuse can damage the motor. Fuses may blow if the motor is overloaded from feeding too rapidly or rapid on/off cycling.</p>

