      <h2>Assembly</h2>

      <h3>Unpacking</h3>
      <p>Reach down to the two side carry-handle locations and slowly lift the saw until it clears the package.</p>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Never lift or move this saw by gripping any component of the mechanism support system.</strong> Severe pinching may occur.
      </div>

      <h3>Attaching the Bevel Lock Lever</h3>
      <p>The saw ships with the head locked at 0&deg; bevel. Attach the bevel lock lever before operating.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Slide the 10 mm flat washer over the shaft (area with flats).</li>
        <li>Slide the bevel lock lever over the shaft, aligning the flats. The lever should be horizontal with the handle to the front.</li>
        <li>Slide the 6 mm flat washer over the threaded portion of the shaft.</li>
        <li>Finger-tighten the 10 mm lock nut, then tighten with the 10 mm socket tool.</li>
        <li>Lift and push the lever to verify it is secure.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Attaching the Miter Lock Knob</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Locate the 10 mm hole under the turntable's front arm.</li>
        <li>Insert the long shaft of the miter lock knob through the hole until it stops.</li>
        <li>Turn clockwise (~10 full revolutions) until tight.</li>
        <li>Loosen 1/2 turn to unlock. The table is now free to move.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Storing the 6/4mm Hex Key</h3>
      <p>Insert the short leg through the rubber grommet on the saw, then place the long leg into the tool rest and press into the retainer clip. This key is needed for blade changes and adjustments.</p>

      <h2>Blade Changes</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Disconnect the plug from the power source before removing or installing blades.</strong>
      </div>

      <h3>Moving the Guard Assembly</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Position the saw in the UP position at 0&deg; bevel. If locked down, press down slightly and pull out the head assembly lock pin.</li>
        <li>Unscrew the link knob by hand from the pivot post; let the link assembly hang.</li>
        <li>Loosen the front cover plate screw two turns using the 6/4 mm hex key. Do not remove.</li>
        <li>Loosen the rear plate screw six full turns. Do not remove.</li>
        <li>Slide the cover plate down and out from the rear screw. Rotate the cover plate and lower guard counterclockwise around the front screw. Move the link so its round hole goes over the rear screw to hold the guard out of the way.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Removing the Blade</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Press and hold the arbor lock (red button). Rotate the blade slowly until it fully seats.</li>
        <li>Using the 6/4 mm hex key, loosen the blade bolt by turning <strong>clockwise</strong> (left-hand threads).</li>
        <li>Remove the blade bolt and outer washer. Slide the blade off the arbor shaft. Leave the inner washer on the shaft.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Installing a 10" Blade</h3>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Use only 10" diameter blades with 5/8" arbor.</strong> Maximum blade plate thickness is 0.103". Use blades rated 4,800 RPM or greater.
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Check that the rotation arrow on the blade matches the rotation arrow on the lower guard.</li>
        <li>Slide the blade up between the sides of the chip deflector, over the arbor shaft, and onto the inner washer's support ring.</li>
        <li>Place the outer washer over the arbor shaft and finger-tighten the blade bolt <strong>counterclockwise</strong> (left-hand threads).</li>
        <li>Press the arbor lock and firmly tighten the blade bolt counterclockwise. Do not over-tighten.</li>
        <li>Reassemble the lower guard and cover plate. Tighten both cover plate screws.</li>
        <li>Reattach the lower guard link to the pivot post. Firmly finger-tighten the link knob.</li>
        <li>Ensure the arbor lock is released so the blade turns freely.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>After installing a new blade,</strong> verify the blade does not interfere with the table insert at 0&deg; and 45&deg; bevel positions. Lower the blade into the blade slot and check for contact with the base or turntable. If contact occurs, seek authorized service.
      </div>

      <h2>Miter/Bevel Adjustments</h2>

      <h3>Calibrating the Miter Detent System</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Engage the miter detent at 0&deg;. Loosen the miter lock knob 1/2 turn.</li>
        <li>Locate four round holes in the miter scale plate. Using a 4 mm hex key, loosen all four screws 1&ndash;2 turns to free the miter detent plate.</li>
        <li>Lock the saw down using the head assembly lock pin.</li>
        <li>Hold a 90&deg; combination square against the fence and rotate the table until the blade is in full contact with the square.</li>
        <li>Tighten all four screws. Reset the miter scale pointer to "0."</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Kerf Insert Adjustment</h3>
      <p>Kerf inserts should be as close to the blade teeth as possible without touching. Lock the saw down, loosen the six kerf screws, adjust, and retighten.</p>

      <h3>0&deg; Bevel Stop Adjustment</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Lock the saw down, slide the head fully back, and set the bevel range selector to "0&ndash;45&deg; Left."</li>
        <li>Tilt the saw left, then rotate right until it hits the vertical stop.</li>
        <li>Use a combination square to verify the blade is 90&deg; to the table.</li>
        <li>If adjustment is needed: loosen bolt heads "A" and "B" (10 mm wrench), loosen set screw "D" (4 mm hex key, 3 turns), then turn set screw "C" until the blade aligns with the square.</li>
        <li>Tighten set screw "D," then bolt heads "A" and "B." Adjust bevel scale pointers to 0&deg;.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>45&deg; Bevel Stop Adjustment</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the bevel range to "0&ndash;45&deg; Left" and tilt fully left to the 45&deg; stop.</li>
        <li>Place the combination square head (45&deg; side) on the table and against the tilted blade.</li>
        <li>If adjustment is needed, turn bolt "F" (8 mm wrench) until the blade plate is in full contact with the square's 45&deg; side.</li>
        <li>Adjust both bevel scale pointers to align with 45&deg; lines.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Bevel Lock Tension</h3>
      <p>If the bevel lock lever is too stiff or does not hold securely:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tilt resistance:</strong> Adjust the large lock nut "H" (24 mm) in 1/16-turn increments.</li>
        <li><strong>Lever tension:</strong> Adjust lock nut "E" (17 mm) in 1/8-turn increments.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Glide System</h2>
      <p>The Axial-Glide system replaces traditional slide rails with an articulating arm mechanism, allowing the saw to be placed flush against a wall while maintaining full sliding capacity.</p>

      <h3>Mechanism Lock Lever</h3>
      <p>Located on the rear left side. Locks the glide system in the full back position (for chop cuts or transport) or the full forward position.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>To engage:</strong> Slide the head assembly to the desired position, then lift the lock lever tab to engage the wedge between the lower housings.</li>
        <li><strong>To release:</strong> Press down on the lock lever tab until the wedge disengages.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Glide Movement Controller</h3>
      <p>Located at the upper joint of the glide mechanism. Adjusts the smoothness of the glide action by slightly tightening or loosening the two screws using a 4 mm hex key.</p>

      <h3>Chop/Crown Lock</h3>
      <p>Locks the head assembly at specific forward positions for maximum capacity chop cuts (up to 5-1/4" tall) or crown molding cuts.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Chop Cut position:</strong> Slide head forward, engage lever into the first hole labeled "Chop Cut."</li>
        <li><strong>Crown Cut position:</strong> Slide head forward, engage lever into the second hole labeled "Crown Cut."</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>Switch Activation</h3>
      <p>Press one of the two switch "Lock-OFF" release buttons with your thumb to disengage the lock, then pull the power switch lever. Release the "Lock-OFF" button. When the switch lever is released, the lock re-engages automatically. A padlock hole (up to 1/4" shackle) is provided for unauthorized use prevention.</p>

      <h3>Electric Brake</h3>
      <p>The automatic electric brake stops the blade in approximately 5 seconds after releasing the trigger. If the brake does not consistently stop the blade within 5 seconds, cycle the saw on/off 4&ndash;5 times without cutting. If it still fails, do not use the saw and have it serviced.</p>

      <div class="note">
        The electric brake is not intended as a safety feature. Always let the blade come to a complete stop before raising it from the workpiece.
      </div>

      <h3>Using the Miter Detent System</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the miter lock knob about 1/2 turn.</li>
        <li>Grip the lock knob, reach down with your index finger, and pull up the miter detent lever.</li>
        <li>Rotate the table to the desired angle as indicated by the miter scale pointer.</li>
        <li>Release the lever into a detent slot or at an angle between detents.</li>
        <li>Tighten the miter lock knob before cutting.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Miter Detent Override</h3>
      <p>When the desired angle is near a standard detent, the override locks out the detent action for micro-adjustments. Pull up the detent lever, press the override button down, then release the lever. To disengage, simply pull the detent lever up again.</p>

      <h3>Chop Cuts</h3>
      <p>A chop cut holds the saw in the rearmost position, operating like a conventional (non-sliding) miter saw. Use the mechanism lock lever or Chop/Crown Lock to fix the head position.</p>

      <h3>Slide Cuts</h3>
      <p>Slide cuts use the Axial-Glide mechanism for wider crosscuts (up to 12"). Pull the saw forward, lower the blade into the workpiece, then push the saw back through the material in a smooth, controlled motion.</p>

      <h3>Bevel Cuts</h3>
      <p>The bevel range selector knob on the right side of the table arm provides three ranges:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Range 1 (default):</strong> 0&ndash;45&deg; left.</li>
        <li><strong>Range 2:</strong> 0&ndash;45&deg; right. Tilt slightly left while rotating the knob to "0&ndash;45&deg; Right."</li>
        <li><strong>Range 3:</strong> Max bevel angle to 47&deg; left or right. Overrides all preset stops.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Compound Cuts</h3>
      <p>A compound cut combines a miter angle (up to 52&deg; left / 60&deg; right) with a bevel angle (up to 47&deg; left or right).</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Do not operate</strong> at the following combination: left bevel 45&deg;&ndash;47&deg; PLUS right miter 46&deg;&ndash;55&deg;. This may cause interference between moving and stationary parts.
      </div>

      <h3>Cutting Grooves</h3>
      <p>Use the depth stop plate and depth stop screw to limit blade depth. Pull the depth stop plate outward, then rotate the depth stop screw to set groove depth. Cut the two outside grooves first, then remove material between cuts by repositioning the workpiece.</p>

      <h3>Crown Molding</h3>
      <p>Crown molding can be cut angled against the table/fence or flat on the table. The saw has special miter detents at 31.6&deg; and bevel detents at 33.9&deg; for cutting 38&deg; spring-angle crown molding flat. For 45&deg; spring-angle molding, use the 35.3&deg; miter setting with a 30&deg; bevel.</p>

      <h2>Dust Collection</h2>
      <p>The dust collection system is mounted on the pivot post, not the upper guard, for superior dust pickup on most cuts.</p>

      <h3>Elbow</h3>
      <p>Attached to the top of the dust chute. Can be rotated in place. Supports either the dust bag or a vacuum cleaner connection. Remove for cleaning by pulling up and twisting; reattach by pressing and twisting until it snaps over the retaining ring.</p>

      <h3>Dust Bag</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Attaching:</strong> Align the coupler slots with the elbow pins, push and twist clockwise.</li>
        <li><strong>Removing:</strong> Twist counterclockwise, then pull off. Always leave the elbow on the dust chute.</li>
        <li><strong>Cleaning:</strong> When 2/3 to 3/4 full, remove the bag, open the bottom zipper over a proper container, and shake vigorously. Clean at the end of each session.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Vacuum Cleaner Attachment</h3>
      <p>The elbow exit port accepts a standard 35 mm diameter vacuum fitting or a 1-1/4" tube. For larger sizes, use an adaptor. Verify the vacuum hose is clear of the mechanism and cutting path before plugging in the saw.</p>

      <h3>Rubber Deflector</h3>
      <p>Extends the range of dust collection. When cutting extra-tall materials (over 2-3/16"), the deflector will contact and flex over the material. It can be folded up and over the back of the dust chute temporarily, or removed by unhooking from the side hooks and rear post.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Dust disposal:</strong> Materials in fine particle form may be explosive. Do not throw sawdust on an open fire. Mixture of oil or water with dust particles may cause spontaneous combustion over time.
      </div>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <h3>Motor Brushes</h3>
      <p>Inspect every 2&ndash;6 months. Remove brush caps with a flat-blade screwdriver. Pull out the brush and check for the wear limit line on the flat side. If the contact face is at or beyond the limit line, replace both brushes as a set. Install with tabs in the correct orientation. Use only genuine Bosch replacement brushes.</p>

      <h3>Drive Belt</h3>
      <p>Periodically inspect by removing the two belt cover screws (#2 Phillips). Clean the area with a brush or compressed air. If the belt is dried out, cracked, or excessively loose, take the saw to an authorized Bosch service center for replacement (special tools required).</p>

      <h3>Cleaning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Always disconnect from power before cleaning.</li>
        <li>Clean most effectively with compressed air (wear safety goggles).</li>
        <li>Keep ventilation openings and switch levers clean and free of debris.</li>
        <li>Remove accumulated sawdust from working parts by blowing or wiping with a damp cloth.</li>
        <li>Do not use gasoline, carbon tetrachloride, chlorinated solvents, or ammonia-based cleaners on plastic parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Blade Care</h3>
      <p>If the saw requires force to cut rather than just guiding, the blade is likely dull or coated with wood pitch. Unplug and remove the blade. Wipe with kerosene or similar solvent to remove gum and pitch. For sharpening, use a professional service unless experienced.</p>

      <h3>Lubrication</h3>
      <p>The tool is factory-lubricated. Regrease gears with special gear lubricant at every brush change. Lubricate moving parts periodically with silicone or light oil spray. Do not use grease (it attracts sawdust). All bearings are sealed for life and require no maintenance.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <h3>Electrical Issues</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Cause</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Brake does not stop blade in ~5 seconds</td>
            <td>Brushes worn, sticking, or not seated; motor overheated; blade bolt loose</td>
            <td>Inspect/clean/replace brushes; use a sharp, recommended blade; let saw cool; tighten blade bolt</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Motor does not start</td>
            <td>Not plugged in; blown fuse; brushes worn</td>
            <td>Plug in / try different outlet; use 15-amp time-delay fuse or breaker; replace brushes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Flash of light from motor endcap when switch released</td>
            <td>Normal brake operation</td>
            <td>No action needed</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>General Issues</h3>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Cause</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Head assembly does not bevel to desired position</td>
            <td>Bevel detent pin engaged at 33.9&deg;; bevel range selector knob limiting movement</td>
            <td>Pull out and rotate the detent pin 1/4 turn; change selector knob position</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Angle of cut not accurate</td>
            <td>Bevel stops at 0&deg; or 45&deg; need adjustment</td>
            <td>See Adjustments section (pages 20&ndash;25 in PDF)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Cannot rotate table</td>
            <td>Miter lock knob tightened; detent lever engaged; sawdust accumulation</td>
            <td>Loosen knob; pull up detent lever; vacuum or blow out dust</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Head assembly will not fully raise</td>
            <td>Lock pin engaged; cover plate loose; sawdust accumulation</td>
            <td>Pull out lock pin; tighten cover plate screws; clean head assembly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Blade binds, jams, or burns wood</td>
            <td>Improper technique; dull blade; wrong blade type; bent blade</td>
            <td>Review operation instructions; replace or sharpen blade; use correct 10" blade</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Head slides during chop cuts</td>
            <td>Mechanism lock lever or Chop/Crown Lock disengaged</td>
